I often wonder if millennials might be the last generation capable of truly appreciating art and connecting with artists without that pressure, without having to view everything through critical lenses.
We grew up in a golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of popular culture, and that collective consciousness has since disappeared.
Back then, we could immerse ourselves directly in content without considering its origins, because tracing it back was not so easy in that era.
We revered these artists as gods, and there was no reason to question this worship. As a result, we built a "quasi-social relationship" with them, regarding it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
While "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday, munching on pizza while binge-watching it.
This is in stark contrast to how we now experience watching shows via streaming platforms. These platforms typically release all 12 episodes at once, allowing everyone to watch at their own pace, with people posting discussions on social media along with "spoiler warnings," or simply engaging in conversations only within specific groups.
In our subconscious, we all yearn for that sense of collective belonging that brings everyone together.
It's precisely this nostalgia that leads us to rewatch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Broadcast News," with their iconic lines becoming viral memes online.
We quote these memorable lines from the shows and movies, assuming that most people will understand the reference.
Now, even if something goes viral online, we cannot assume that everyone has seen it.
With information exploding now, there are so many things we need to pay attention to that it's impossible to simplify them… Do we still have the chance to escape this state of information overload?
We discover new media and new artists one after another, only to find that they are either notorious sexual abusers or stubborn bigots peddling prejudice, and this cycle just wears us out.
On one hand, we are trapped in nostalgia, while on the other hand, we have to admit that the creators of the art we love might have serious moral flaws, and this contradictory mindset leaves us at a loss.
We will be even more cautious in establishing "virtual social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realize that if someone wants to acquire wealth and power, it becomes difficult to avoid hurting or exploiting others.
Since collective consciousness has disappeared from the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Naturally, some people remain痴迷未悟, insisting on elevating others to godlike status only to look shocked when their idols fall.
We are living in a time of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
